               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "#### The *Yupana*\n\nWe also learned that reading the quipu was done with the help of tools such as the yupana, which also records numbers vertically, as we can see in the work of Felipe Guaman Poma de Ayala:",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p style=\"margin: auto; width: 100%;\"><iframe src=\"https://archive.org/details/primer-nueva-coronica-y-buen-gobierno-manuscrito/page/n361/mode/2up\" width=\"100%\" height=\"560\" frameborder=\"0\" webkitallowfullscreen=\"true\" mozallowfullscreen=\"true\" allowfullscreen></iframe></p><p class=\"desc\">Book 1: Page 362, Felipe Guaman Poma de Ayala's book.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": [
                  {
                     "type": "gregory",
                     "year": "2015",
                     "month": "4",
                     "day": "26"
                  }
               ],
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "On this image, we see an Indigenous man holding a quipu (knotted cords), with a numerical value indicated on the right. To the left, there is a Yupana—a board with dots representing numbers, possibly associated with finger counting.",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": " "
            },
            {
               "text": "#### The Method\n\nSince no known Inca texts describe how the yupana was used, it is necessary to carry out studies that attempt to understand how it might have been employed. One such study was conducted by Dhavit Prem, who identified five possible movements to perform with the yupana, enabling mathematical operations (<htcite0>; <htcite1>). These movements were explained in detail in his article and also when we teach addition with the *yupana* (<htcite2>).\n\nBelow, select the movement you wish to perform on the yupana and then use the arrow <i class=\"fa-solid fa-arrows-left-right\" style=\"color:#0f0;\"></i> to move the circles, and <i class=\"fa-solid fa-arrows-rotate\" style=\"color:#00f;\"></i> to update the fingers of the hands, and return to the original position:",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "a62b520a-f443-4d83-ab51-b99c9a46dab8",
                     "text": "Prem, Dhavit",
                     "page": "pp. 354 - 363",
                     "date_time": {
